segments.text: This is an interview with Ron Essig by Mary Cook on November 25, 1988, at the home of Ron Essig.
In the interest of accumulating knowledge about the war, I am going to donate this tape to the Texas A&M Oral History Collection and the University Archives.
Is that all right with you?
Mm-hmm.
Okay.
Okay, the first question is, where were you born?
Reading, Pennsylvania.
Okay.
And when were you born?
What year?
And where did you go to school?
Wilson High School, West Long, Pennsylvania.
Okay.
And did you attend college?
No.
And when and where did you join the military?
I joined it in Pennsylvania in August of 1966.
And what was the reason for joining the military?
There was no main reason.
I just went and joined.
Did you join...
Because of Vietnam?
No, that had nothing to do with it.
And what was the extent of your military training before arriving in Vietnam?
Well, I took my basic training.
I took helicopter training in Fort Rucker, Alabama, and then from there I went right to Vietnam.
And what were your feelings when you found out you were being sent to Vietnam?
Well, I was scared at first, but...
There was nothing I could do about it, so I went.
And what were the sentiments, did you feel, in the country at the time that you were sent to Vietnam, as far as what were... Did you feel there was a lot of anti-war sentiment at the time?
Was it prevalent in Pennsylvania, or...?
Not really.
When I went to Vietnam, it really wasn't that much.
So it was still a positive attitude.
Right.
We felt we should be in Vietnam.
Right.
After I was over there, that's when it really got started.
Okay.
What was your initial reaction upon arriving in Vietnam?
Well, it wasn't what I expected.
I expected to see bullets flying, but it was nothing like that.
I mean, where I reported into in Vietnam was...
what they called a coal area.
It was an induction center.
And I was there about four days before I got sent to my company.
I really didn't see any action until I was there about a month, I guess, when we first finally got hit by mortars.
And where were you?
What part of Vietnam were you at the time?
In the northern part, in the highlands, at Da Nang.
Da Nang.
Did you, were you around the people, the Vietnamese people at all?
How did you feel about the people?
Around the Vietnamese people all the time.
They, well, I was just amazed how the people lived.
You know, it was such a poor country.
And I just couldn't comprehend how they could live the way they did.
You know, of course, being, you know, from the United States and everything, we had everything we wanted.
And then going to a country like that where it was so poor and their way of life, I just took a while for it to sink in.

Did you try, I don't know, some units, we've had people talk to us, some of the men would help the villagers or the natives around where they were as far as the different things to improve their living.
Were you involved with that at all?
No, our company was.
We were an aviation company.
Okay, do you feel you understood the Vietnamese people and their culture at all?
Do you feel you understood why they lived the way they did and they were happy with the way they were living, apparently?
Oh, yeah, they were definitely happy.
Well, I mean, it was their way of life.
Right.
As far as the war...
No, they weren't happy with that.
Was it because we were there?
Were they not happy with our presence?
Would they have rather fought the war themselves?
No, I didn't take it that way.
I'm cut for words now.
I never felt that much hatred toward the American GI while I was there.
In a sense, you know, they were glad that we were there helping them and everything.
But when it came really down to the fighting, I mean, you get to the soldier of the South Vietnamese Army, I felt like he could have done more if he would have tried harder.
But as far as the civilian people, yeah, I feel like they were pleased that we were there.
And what unit were you in?
282nd Assault Helicopter Company.
Okay.
And what was your mission?
Resupply, medevac, troop lift.
So you were carrying out supplies to troops?
Right.
We supported the 1st Arvin Division, the South Vietnamese soldiers.
Okay.
And was that division, the Arvin Division, did you find they were well-trained, well-equipped to deal with what was going on?
Well...
As far as the training, no, they didn't have very good training, but they were supplied by the United States government.
I mean, they were American weapons.
Right.
And how long were you in Vietnam?
A year and a half.
And as far as usually we're under the impression, or I'm under the impression, that most people were only over there for a year.
Right.
And is there a reason why you were over there
Well, when it was time for my year was up, I had about 16 months to go in the service yet.
And I knew if I'd come back to the States, I'd only be back a few months and I'd have to go right back to Vietnam again.
So I just stayed an additional six months and then came back to the States and get out of the service when I got back.
How did you and your unit, okay, you were a supply unit.
Could you describe to me exactly what that entailed as far as?
Well, as far as supply, we'd resupply them with weapons, ammunition, medical supplies, food.
So you'd fly out to the different areas and drop off these supplies and then come back to the base area, which was Da Nang?
Mm-hmm.
And did you see a lot of, when you landed, when you tried to drop off supplies and that kind of thing, were you under fire a lot of times or?
About 50% of the time.
We've seen quite a bit of hostile fire.
Okay.
What was the training of your unit?
Were all the men in your unit
Did they go through the same training that you did back in the States?
No.
Well, the ones that went to the training I did were the crew chiefs and the mechanics.
And then we had gunners.
They consisted mostly of infantry.
One gunner I had was with the 1st Infantry Division, and he transferred to the aviation unit to be a door gunner.
And that was his main duty, was just a gunner.
Take care of the guns.
It was my job to maintain the helicopter and see that it would fly.
And then while we were flying, and then I was a gunner.
Would you say that the training that you had then prepared you for, I mean, as far as not for the war aspect, not for what you expected when you got there, but...
the training that you did have, you were prepared when you were over there to do your job, your specific job of taking care of the helicopter.
Yeah, definitely.
And going back now, going back to different battles in Vietnam, you were over there during Tet.
What was your first reaction to Tet?
Well,
It was very hostile, I know that.
When it initially started, it wasn't too bad for me.

Well, I mean, as far as our company, the ones that were stationed at Da Nang, we had, we kept, our main base was at Da Nang, and we kept helicopters to the north at Way Citadel and helicopters to the south at Quang Ngai.
And we really didn't get into the heavy fighting of it until they more or less overran Way...
Rover ran away Citadel.
And then that's when we really had to get in some heavy fighting.
Then...
So that was your unit that got into it.
Right.
And I was scared then.
And did you fly on these... You were out on these missions then?
Oh, yeah.
Got in some really heavy fighting then.
And...
So, did you think...
Well, did you know it was coming?
Did you have any idea what that tap was going to occur?

They tried to prepare us for it, but I don't think, as far as the commanding officers in our company, I don't think they realized it would be as intense as it was and it would last as long as it did, which I can't tell the exact amount of days that it lasted, but
I honestly believe that they only figured it would last maybe five or six days.
Right.
And it carried way beyond that.
So it was an intensive period of fighting for an extensive period of time.
It was fighting 24 hours a day.
And the U.S., you don't believe that the U.S. actually knew what they were getting into when they carried out this?
Well...
I think the intelligence part probably did, but like I said, as far as the commanding officers of the company that I was in, I don't think they knew it was gonna be that bad.
Okay, and how did you... You said you were scared about the fighting, the intensive fighting.
How did... What other feelings were going through your mind?
I mean...
personal feelings, and this is a difficult question, but... Well, if you're trying to ask me, the question is, did I think we should have been over there?
No, that's a question later on.

But did you personally, at the time of Tet, when you were doing this fighting, when you were involved in the intensive fighting in your unit, besides being scared, do you remember any other feelings that were going through your mind?
Or just get out of there and get home.
That's all I was concerned about.
And you had, at that time, you had about ten, nine, nine months left, was it?
Yeah, it was about nine months.
And what about your choice to go ahead and stay over there?
Did you feel that that was...
I still felt like I made the right choice.
What were the, after Tet, what was the feeling of your unit, of the troops, of the US troops in Vietnam?
Were they more enthusiastic because Tet was supposedly a win for us?
Oh, definitely.
So they were more enthusiastic about being in Vietnam?
Yeah, I feel they were.
And did it motivate you personally, Tet?
In a sense, I guess it did, yeah.
I don't know.
I figured if I could make it through that mess, I can make it through anything and just get home and forget about it.
What was the military leadership like?
What were your commanding officers like?
Were they trained for Vietnam?
Were they experienced with war?
Oh, yeah.
We had...
quite a number of them that were on their second and third tours over there.
You know, they knew what it was about and they worked with the men to make sure that they got through it.
So you feel like their leadership was adequate?
Oh, yeah.
Did they ever ask
the men in your unit to do something which you felt or the men in your unit felt was totally unreasonable.

I know in the military there's supposedly no room for, you do what you're told and there's no room for questioning, but in one of the books that we had read, and I know this wasn't in your unit, it wasn't a duty of yours, but they were to search the tunnels and they always had to search the tunnels.
I'm just wondering if there was anything that the leadership in your unit told you to do that was putting the men in your unit's life in danger more than... Not that I really recall.
Everything just clicked along pretty smooth.
Okay.
Was there a problem with drug use in your unit?
Yeah, quite a bit.
Why do you think drugs were such a major factor in the Vietnam War with men?
I think a lot of guys feared they had to have it to get through it.
So it was a crutch.
It was a big hide to them.
It just, I don't know, maybe made them face reality or something.
I don't know.
Marijuana was a big demand.
Marijuana.
Yeah.
Were other drugs in use at the time?
Not that I know of.
And it was readily available?
Oh, yeah.
You just go downtown and buy that like you buy a pack of cigarettes.
And what about the commanding officers?
They obviously knew.
Oh, sure they knew.
And did they use it also?
That I really don't know.
I've never seen them do it.
But
What they did on their free time was their business.
Okay.
Was there, okay, you said this was in some of the commanding officers, this was their second or third tour.
Was that because of careerism?
Were they in the military as a career?
Yeah.
And did you?
were you aware of or did you see any altering of official reports?
In some instances, as in body counts, body counts were upped as far as the enemy.
Conditions weren't reported as being as bad as they were.
Some conditions were reported very optimistically in order for their backgrounds to look better.
Did you see that happening?
I haven't seen it happen, no.
Do you have any particular operation which you consider the least successful of your unit?
Not really.
It seemed like everything we did was, well, to me, everything we did seemed successful.
I mean, we never lost that many people.
Not while I was over there.
And what happened before I was there or after I was there, I really don't know.
Right.
I mean, we lost some people, but we didn't lose that many.
So, you know, if you go out on a mission and come back with as many people going out, it was a success.
Right.
And you consider the number of people you lost to be?
It was a minimum.
Minimum.
Okay.
And is there any particular mission you consider the most successful?
Or would you just write them all down?
I'd read them all about the same, really.
About the same.
Okay, and you were, when we were talking about the Vietnamese, and you said, you, did you feel like you understood the Vietnamese as far as the people go?
You said you did not.
Was that correct?
I mean, as far as, because you didn't understand why they lived the way they did.
Well, I knew why they lived the way they did, because they were poor.
It was a poor country.
It was communism.
But they seemed happy living that way.
That's how they lived all their life.
Okay.
How did you feel about the Arvin?
They were lazy.
Really.
You know, like I said earlier, their training could have been a lot better.
Do you blame their lack of training on their lack of ambition?
Yeah.
Because if we take a troop lift out,
We drop off the first wave of troops, go back up and pick the second wave up, and we come right back to where we were the first ones.
The first one was still sitting there.
I mean, they didn't even make an effort to move.
It looked like they were just going out on a camping trip.
That was it.
They were already cooking their rice, so, you know, there was definitely a lack of effort.
And do you feel like we should have just, you said they're lazy, do you feel, I mean, you were out there, you were putting your life on the line, and you dropped them off and they'd sit there.
I mean, did you feel like you should have just said, well, bye, I'm going home and left?
I mean, you know, do you feel like we should have just said bye and let them fight their own war and take care of it the way they wanted to?
Well, at first I didn't think that, but when it came close to the end of my tour, then I realized what was going on.
So after you've been over there over a year.
Right, you know, when you're there your first six months, you know, you have to be there that long to see what's really going on.
You just can't see it in one or two days.
But when it came close to the end of my tour, I just...
I figured it was just a waste, which it really was.
So, basically, I guess the next question is, do you resent putting your life on the line?
Do you resent the time that you spent 18 months over there?
The first six months, it took you six months to figure out what was going on.
Then you dropped these men off.
They didn't do what they were supposed to do.
We were over there, we were supplying them, equipping them, spending millions, millions of dollars.
Do you resent being over there?
Do you resent that 18 months of your life?
No, I don't resent being there.
I did something I had to do.
The United States government said, hey, you're going to Vietnam, and that was it.
So I served my time just like anybody else did.
There was no sense in protesting it.
It wouldn't do no good.
So I did my duty and that was it.
How do you feel, or how did you feel about the North Vietnamese Army?
How, what were their, do you feel like they were that much better trained, equipped than the South?
Well, they were trained better.
They were much more disciplined.
When it came up to Ted, and they started coming down from the north, I mean they were, they were running short on troops and stuff.
I mean they were sending 12, 13 year old children down to fight.
But they were still disciplined.
They did what they were told to do.
And as far as their weapons, yeah I think they had pretty good weapons.
They were all communist made.
From what we captured of them, they seemed like pretty decent weapons.
How were they treated when they were captured?
Not too good.
Can you give me a specific?
Well, they were bounced around pretty good.
You know, if they captured three or four of them, they wouldn't talk.
They'd bounce one of them around pretty good to make the others talk.
So it was a pretty tough interrogation they put them through.
Now, that was the Vietnamese that did the interrogating.
Now, I never saw how the Americans interrogated them.
So this was the South Vietnamese interrogating the North?
Right, the South Vietnamese that interrogated them.
They had no mercy on them, which I'm sure it was the same way with the North.
And how did you feel about the Viet Cong?
Since you really couldn't, how did you pick the Viet Cong?
How did you pick out Viet Cong from the Arvin?
Well, they were, the Viet Cong, they were, you could tell them.
They mostly wore black pajamas and stuff.
Where the South Vietnamese Army, they wore green fatigues and stuff like we did.
Hey, that sucker had a gun.
He was pointing it at me.
It was either him or me.
Was there a lot of Arvin by day and Viet Cong by night?
That kind of thing?
That I really couldn't tell you.
I don't know.
There was a lot of stories about it.
OK, now back to the President of the United States and different policies that he had at the time.
What about during Vietnam?
What about LBJ and his, we're going to bomb only certain places and you have to ask my permission to bomb?
And it was basically for a time, I don't know when you were over there or how it ran, but for a time it was a nine to five war, basically.
And it was not fought during the holidays.
Right.
How did you feel about that?
It was a war.
I mean... Well, as far as the bombing, I didn't agree with the way he did it.
I think if he had just went out there and bombed the north and got it over with, it probably would have ended a lot quicker.
That's my feeling.
I might be wrong.
I don't know.
But as far as bombing here and bombing there and shutting it down for so many days and then reasonable,
start the bombing again.
I didn't agree with it.
Like I said, they just would have went in there with a squadron of bombers and unloaded on them.
I think they could have stopped it.
And as far as that getting clearance to fire, I've been through that too many times.
You know, you see something on the ground, you know it's not right, then you have to call in for clearance to fire and it'd take anywhere from 30 to 45 minutes to get clearance.
It's all gone.
So did you always get clearance to fire?
Sometimes we did.
Sometimes we didn't.
We didn't take matters into our own hands.
And you did what you felt was right.
And sometimes we'd even have a South Vietnamese commanding officer on board, but we'd still have to call for clearance.
We couldn't get clearance.
He'd give us a word, go ahead and fire, so we'd fire.
Was this the attitude of your whole unit?
I mean, was, as far as the policies?
Were the men in your unit, did they feel the same way about the bombing policy and about clearing, getting clearance to fire and that kind of thing?
Oh, yeah.
The whole company felt the same about it.
What did you think about the government's role in Vietnam as far as LBJ's policy?
Later on, Nixon, when he said he was going to withdraw troops and then we invaded Cambodia, how did you feel about...
It was very political, the whole thing.
How did you feel about that as far as...
It was more politics running the war than the military was running the war.
Do you feel like the military...
The upper officers really had any kind of control, or do you think they were more controlled by what was politically happening in the United States?
It was all run from Washington.
I mean, the commanding officers, I mean, of our company, they had to take orders from battalion.
Battalion had to take them from there higher up.
So it was definitely politics.
We had no control.
We had to do what we were told to do, and that was it.
Okay.
Were you aware when you were over in Vietnam of the media involvement in the war?
Did you know what was being broadcast in the United States about the war?
Not when I was over there, I didn't.
I didn't realize it until I got home.
Were there any media...
around TV reporters, camera, newspaper photographers, that kind of thing.
Did you ever see any while you were in?
No, I never saw any.
Were you aware of the anti-war sentiment that was increasing in the United States while you were in Vietnam?
Yeah.
And how did that?
My parents used to send me newspaper clippings of it.
kind of made me mad, knowing that I was over there trying to serve my country and then had these protesters back in the States going against the war.
Then you had some that went to Canada trying to avoid the war.
So, yeah, I was mad.
And what did your parents say about you being in Vietnam?
Did they support you being in Vietnam?
Or when you came home, did they not want to hear about your Vietnam experiences?
Oh, they wanted to hear about them.
You know, but at first I couldn't talk about it.
I just, something I had to get out of my mind.
Now, it was kind of tough for my parents because it was myself and my brother, we were both over at the same time.
So it was kind of hard on my parents.
But, uh,
As far as when we came back, I mean, there was no hard feelings or anything like that.
Did you, when you came back, what was your reception?
I don't know.
You went back to Pennsylvania.
Mm-hmm.
Were you from a small town in Pennsylvania?
No, it was a pretty good-sized city.
Pretty good-sized.
And what about the people you knew?
How did they treat you when you came back?
Well, at first...
I don't know, I guess they might have thought I was going to come back whacked out or something.
I don't know.
At first they were just kind of easy.
They were kind of careful what they said and stuff.
But after I was home a while, it just more or less tapered out like it used to be.
Good old drinking buddies and stuff.
The only experience that I really had that kind of really hit me
was when I flew from California to Pennsylvania.
I was on a plane and a woman looked at me and just, for no reason at all, she just looked at me and called me a child murderer.
I guess because it was a Vietnam man.
I wasn't gonna let it bother me.
I was going home.
So you wore your uniform from California to Pennsylvania?
And when this woman said that to you, it was, what could you say?
It was a shock at first, you know, hey, wait a minute, I didn't kill no kids.
But that's just the way that people were.
You know, the Vietnam vet, he took a bad rap.
It's just been the last few years that they've really been doing something for him.
You mentioned about people that chose Canada instead of serving their country.
How do you feel about those people?
If you met somebody that came up to you and said, oh, you're a Vietnam War vet, well, I went to Canada instead, what would you say to that person?
I don't think I'd say anything to them.
Just for the satisfaction, I'd probably smack them in the mouth and get it over with.
You know, it was...
my way of thinking he was a coward.
You know, hey, if I'm good enough to serve my country, so is he.
I lived through it.
Do you think that's part of being a citizen of the United States, to serve your country?
Even if you don't feel the reason for... Well, I feel like it is.
...being involved is correct?
Right.
When we were talking about politics involved in the war,
And the anti-war movement, do you feel the anti-war movement was more against what was occurring in Washington than against the military?
Do you think people were really against the military, or is it just the government policy at the time?
I think they were against the government.
That's what I think.
And you said you wore your uniform from when you got back into the state.
And some people came back to the States from Vietnam, some veterans.
One incident, he took his uniform off as soon as he got into California before he went home.
Some of them have joined anti-war movements when they got back to the States.
They were not proud about their role in Vietnam.
Can you say that you are proud of your role in Vietnam?
Yeah, I was proud of what I did.
I served my country.
They sent me over there to do a job.
I felt like I did a job.
Would you say that Vietnam, the reason for us being in Vietnam and or the people were worth dying for if you had lost or killing for when you were over there?

As far as stopping communism, yeah, it was worth it, but for the people that were there, and like I said, after the way I saw how they operated, I mean, as far as the military, no, I can't agree with that.
Not on the part of the South Vietnamese military.
If they'd have tried harder, they could have done it.
But when the United States pulled out, they just...
More or less threw up their hands and said, hey, here we are.
That's the way it looked to me.
Right.
Do you think if we would have pulled out, or if we hadn't been over there, or we would have pulled out sooner, do you think they would have just done the same thing, just said, well, forget it?
Yeah, I think they would have.
What are your views on the Selective Service, on National Guard?
What about the men that joined the National Guard instead of, well, after a period of time, they weren't allowed in the National Guard anyways, but... Well, I won't hold anything against them for it.
Somebody had to go in the National Guard.
Might sound like a stupid answer, but... No, I don't hold anything against anybody who went in the National Guard.
And what about the Selective Service?
Did you feel like they were trained?
Did you feel like they did their job, that they were trained better?
No.
I think they did all right.
I mean, they did what they were told to do.
They were trained to do that job, and that's what they did.
And the last question is, do you think we could have won the war?
That's a hard one to answer.
In fact, that's the first time anybody's ever asked me that question.
Yeah, I think we could have.
Well, we'll go right back to the bombing again.
If they would have continued the bombing,
And kept bombing and bombing and bombing.
Eventually, yeah, they would have got him down to where we could have beat him.
So going back to the very, not the very beginning, but to LBJ's getting us more involved to his policy on bombing, if we would have just gone over there and bombed...
I think so.
It would have taken care of it.
I think it would have.
And we would have been out of there a lot sooner.
I feel like we would have, yeah.
Would have saved a lot more lives too.
Okay.
Is there any... Is there anything I haven't touched on that maybe you'd like to... No, you hit a lot more than I thought you were going to hit.
Are there any experiences that... Not really.
How do you feel today about...
I know I said that was the last question, but...
About the movies that are out about Vietnam, there's, well, there was Good Morning Vietnam.
There's Hamburger Hill, Platoon, Rambo.
Well, I've seen nearly all of them.
And the closest thing that I've seen in the movies to Vietnam was Platoon.
Platoon?
Mm-hmm.
Of course, now that was all infantry.
I didn't get into the jungles like they did.
And that good morning Vietnam, it was... That was more of a political... On a scale of one to ten, I give it a zero.
But it, no, it doesn't have any effect on me.
I imagine some of these Vietnam vets it probably does.
Well, thank you very much.
